## 1. Understanding the Architecture

Your app has these moving parts:

```mermaid
graph LR
    A[Faculty Browser] -->|HTTPS| B[Your Server]
    B --> C[Flask App + Gunicorn]
    C --> D[(SQLite / PostgreSQL)]
    C --> E[InsightFace AI Model]
    C --> F[face_database.json]
    C --> G[registered_faces/ images]
```

| Component | What it does |
|---|---|
| **Flask + Gunicorn** | Web server — handles requests |
| **SQLite DB** | Stores students, faculty, attendance, timetable |
| **face_database.json** | Maps person_id → image paths & metadata |
| **face_embeddings_insightface.pkl** | Pre-computed face vectors for fast recognition |
| **registered_faces/** | Actual face images (JPEGs) |
| **yolov8n-face.pt** | YOLO model for detecting faces in group photos |

---

## 2. Database: SQLite vs PostgreSQL

### Should you switch?

| Factor | SQLite (Current) | PostgreSQL |
|---|---|---|
| **Setup** | Zero config, one file | Requires a separate server |
| **Cost** | Free | Free tier available (Neon, Supabase) |
| **Concurrent users** | ⚠️ 1 writer at a time | ✅ Many simultaneous writers |
| **Data loss risk** | ⚠️ File can get corrupted on crash | ✅ ACID-compliant, crash-safe |
| **Cloud hosting** | ⚠️ Ephemeral file systems lose data on redeploy | ✅ Persistent, separate service |
| **Scale** | Good for ~50 users | Good for 1000+ users |

> [!IMPORTANT]
> **Recommendation:** For a real college deployment with multiple faculty using it simultaneously, **switch to PostgreSQL**. Most cloud platforms (Railway, Render) have **free/cheap file systems that reset on every deploy**, which means your SQLite DB would be **wiped every time you push an update**. PostgreSQL runs as a separate persistent service that survives redeploys.

### If you want to start simple first
You *can* keep SQLite for an initial test/demo by using a platform with persistent disk (like a DigitalOcean Droplet or a VPS). But for long-term, PostgreSQL is the way to go.

